snippet.textDisplay: Pro tip...don't do your burnout IN the water box. Roll into the water..blip the throttle to make the tires spin so the entire wheel gets wet. Pull up to a dry spot and THEN do your burnout. Your low wheel speed burnouts in the water box are basically enough to get the water off but not heat the tires up. If you aren't seeing smoke then your wheels are not warm at all.

snippet.textDisplay: engineering pro tip: solid vs tube is mostly meaningless. The shear stress in a cylindrical shaft is overwhelmingly carried by the outer ring, hence why tubes are preferred practically everywhere that weight and material cost is an issue. The only real advantage of a solid shaft is that it's more resistant to physical damage and extreme changes in torque. As a heavier rotating mass it also has more momentum/inertia, which can help or hurt you depending on what you are after.
